'''Arabs''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|ær|ə|b|z|}};<ref>{{cite web|title=Arabs – Wiktionary|url=https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Arabs|website=en.wiktionary.org|language=en}}</ref> {{lang-ar|عَرَبٌ}}, <small>[[ISO 233]]</small> {{transl|ar|‘arab}}; <small>Arabic pronunciation:</small> {{IPA-ar|ˈʕarab||Arabspronouncedar.oog.ogg}}) are a population inhabiting the [[Arab world]]. They primarily live in the [[Member states of the Arab League|Arab states]] in [[Western Asia]], [[North Africa]], the [[Horn of Africa]] and western [[List of islands in the Indian Ocean|Indian Ocean islands]] (including the [[Comoros]]), as well as in significant numbers in the [[Americas]], [[Western Europe]], [[Indonesia]], [[Israel]], [[Turkey]] and [[Iran]].<ref name=":0" /> The [[Arab diaspora]] is established around the world.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bureš|first1=Jaroslav|title=Main characteristic and development trends of migration in the Arab world|date=2008|publisher=Institute of International Relations|location=Prague|isbn=978-8086506715}}</ref>

The first mention of Arabs is from the mid-ninth century BCE as a tribal people in eastern and southern [[Syria (region)|Syria]] and the north of the [[Arabian Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Myers|first1=E. A.|title=The Ituraeans and the Roman Near East: Reassessing the Sources|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781139484817|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-cRrGQ8bIAkC|page=18|date=11 February 2010}}</ref> The Arabs appear to have been under the [[vassal]]age of the [[Neo-Assyrian Empire]] (911–612 BCE), and the succeeding [[Neo-Babylonian Empire|Neo-Babylonian]] (626–539 BCE), [[Achaemenid Empire|Achaemenid]] (539–332 BCE), [[Seleucid Empire|Seleucid]], and [[Parthian Empire|Parthian]] empires.<ref>
